3D Fire + Air Entropy Visualization (Taichi)
this is small interactive 3d simulation that shows fire-like rising particles + "air" particles trapped inside a cube.
the air particles are used to calculate very simple "entropy" in little 5×5×5 grid cubes → then we color those cubes depending how "mixed" or "crowded" the air is inside each small volume.
main idea:

orange/yellow/red particles = fire rising from small disc at bottom
white particles = air molecules bouncing inside invisible cube
colored semi-transparent cubes = visualization of local entropy (more red = higher entropy / more disorder)

main features

realistic-ish fire look with temperature-based color fade (white→yellow→orange→red→dark)
fire particles feel pushed away by their own density (using very simple grid gradient)
air particles bounce on cube walls and push each other a little (basic elastic swap)
entropy shown as 5×5×5 grid of colored semi-transparent cubes
low entropy → blue-ish
high entropy → red-ish
gui sliders to play with energy, emission rate, max particles etc
press r → reset everything
wasd + qe → simple camera movement

important parameters you can change at top
PythonMAX_FIRE = 60_000          # max number of fire particles
MAX_AIR  = 10_000          # max number of air particles
EMIT_RATE = 6000           # how many fire particles per second (approx)
PARTICLE_LIFETIME = 1.7    # how long fire lives (seconds)

EMITTER_RADIUS = 0.20      # size of fire source disc
BASE_UPWARD_SPEED = 1.5    # base rising speed

GRID_CELL_SIZE = 0.1       # size of density grid cell for fire push
GRID_SIZE_X/Y/Z = 48       # density grid resolution

ENTROPY_GRID_DIV = 5       # 5×5×5 = 125 entropy cubes
cube_half = 2.5            # cube goes from -2.5..2.5 in x/z and 0..2.5 in y
how the entropy part works (simplified)

every frame we count how many air particles are in each small cube (5×5×5 grid)
we calculate very simple "entropy" using stirling approx of ln(n!)
(right now we use n * log(n) - n scaled by boltzmann_k=1.0)
find maximum entropy value in this frame
normalize every cell entropy against that max → get 0..1 value
map 0 → blue, 1 → red (with pow(0.35) gamma so low values are more visible)
write same color to all 8 vertices of that cube
render as semi-transparent mesh (alpha=0.28)

note: current entropy is still negative most of time because of -n term.
this means almost everything stays blue unless you have very high particle counts.
many people change it to just use particle count directly (s_val = n) or n * log(n+1) to make colors more lively.
quick ways to improve colors right now
change this part in calculate_entropy() kernel:
Python# option A - just use particle count (easiest, works immediately)
entropy_grid_entropy[i,j,k] = n
ti.atomic_max(max_entropy_val[None], n + 1e-4)

# option B - positive growing value
entropy_grid_entropy[i,j,k] = n * ti.log(n + 1.0)
ti.atomic_max(max_entropy_val[None], n * ti.log(n + 1.0) + 1e-4)
then colors start to make more sense (more particles = redder)
known small issues / things to improve

no real turbulence / vorticity for air (just basic bounce + gradient push)
particles drawn twice sometimes (two scene.particles(pos) calls — to ensure the constant rendering of the particles over the cubes)
no shadows or fancy lighting (just one point light + ambient)

controls cheat sheet

r          → reset simulation
a / d     → rotate left/right
w / s     → zoom in/out
q / e     → camera height up/down
sliders:
energy            → affects fire speed & color temperature
emit rate         → how fast new fire appears
max fire particles -- not working properly
max air particles


have fun playing with it!
